commitResults.messageTitle: Added basic functions for Task class

commitResults.messageBody:
The if/else nest was too deep.

Using enums for instructions is easier for bug catching and future
expansions.

The instructions enum is declared at the top of the file
The nested if/else is written as a switch case instead.

Each task will type their own type into the status.

To save the tasks into the data file we need to be able to access the
type indicator for each task.

Declare type into Task class and instantiate them within each inherited
class.

Now each task can access their own types.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add function to retrieve type of Task
commitResults.messageBody:
Previous commit required this function.

The function has now been added so each Task can access their own type
for writting data.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add function to convert task to textline
commitResults.messageBody:
To convert the task into 1 line of txt to save the tasks easily.

Deadline and Event class overwrites the function to add the additional
parameters.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add function to convert textline to Task
commitResults.messageBody:
To simplify the process for creating Tasks after reading from the txt
file.

Whenever the program stops running the tasks will be lost.

To ensure that the list of tasks is kept, save the tasks into a local
txt file and read it the next time the program is run.

commitResults.messageTitle: Change functions to recognise date and time
commitResults.messageBody:
Variables such as the deadline or start and end of events are stored as
Strings.

It makes more sense to store them as LocalDateTime for logical
validation.

Changed the declaration of the classes involved from String to
LocalDateTime.
Added functions in main class to convert between String and
LocalDateTime and replaced parts of the function to save and load from
the text file.

commitResults.messageTitle: Extract functions into Packages and Objects
commitResults.messageBody:
Almost all functions were defined in the main Klee class.

This is very untidy and makes it difficult to navigate the code.

Extract functions into Objects and put similar classes into packages.
command package includes all commands that Klee accepts.
tasks package includes all types of tasks that Klee can note down.
General commands are split into general classes within Klee package.
